Anonymous Thu 21 Apr 2022 05:53:40 No.47099078 Report
Quoted By: >>47099181 >>47103823
Hey, DoubleCenterfold, I'm going through Strange Deviations right now. I'll give my full thoughts in a couple of days, but I figured I would share this right now because I'm not sure if you've heard this before and it's pretty important.
Novel writers generally strive for about 14 to 20 words average in a sentence, with some room for playing around during both drawn out descriptions and choppy action scenes. They also tend to keep the number of commas in a given sentence to two or less.
Your prose averages at like 50+ words and 5+ commas per sentence. That's a pretty big deviation from the average novel, and my impression is that it isn't intentional. It really hurts the quality of your work when combined with the syntax errors scattered throughout the piece. It reads like the equivalent of listening to your Grandpa ramble on about Korea while his sleep meds kick in.
You have to utilize more full breaks. When you use a balanced mix of punctuation, your prose flows much more naturally than it would if you just perpetuate the sentence on and on with an endless supply of commas.
